---
import '../../styles/global.css';
import LessonLayout from '../../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
import LessonHeader from '../../components/LessonHeader.astro';
import LessonNav from '../../components/LessonNav.astro';
import InsightBox from '../../components/InsightBox.astro';
import TagBadge from '../../components/TagBadge.astro';
import GraphForwardDemo from '../../components/demos/GraphForwardDemo.astro';
---

<LessonLayout title="The Forward Pass" lessonNumber="1.2" section="The Graph">

    <LessonHeader lessonNumber="1.2" title="The Forward Pass" description="Running the graph left to right: push numbers in, compute each node, get an output. The twist is that while it computes, it also remembers, which is what makes going backward possible.">
        <TagBadge variant="concepts">concepts</TagBadge>
        <TagBadge variant="default">8 min read</TagBadge>
    </LessonHeader>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Left to right.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            The <strong>forward pass</strong> is the obvious half: start at the leaves, evaluate each operation in
            order, and carry the results forward until you reach the output. It's just doing the arithmetic the graph
            describes. Watch it ripple through <span class="font-mono">e = (a &times; b) + c</span>:
        </p>

        <GraphForwardDemo />
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">A walk through, by hand.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            With <span class="font-mono">a = 2, b = -3, c = 10</span>:
        </p>
        <div class="bg-white border border-mt-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-4 font-mono text-sm space-y-1">
            <div>d = a &times; b = 2 &times; (-3) = -6</div>
            <div>e = d + c = -6 + 10 = <strong>4</strong></div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed">
            That's the whole forward pass: two operations, one output. Nothing surprising. The interesting part is what
            happens <em>alongside</em> the computing.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Computing and remembering at once.</h2>
        <p class="text-mt-muted leading-relaxed mb-4">
            As each operation runs, it does two things, not one. It computes its output value, and it records two facts
            about itself: <strong>which values were its inputs</strong>, and <strong>what operation it was</strong>.
            That record is what lets the backward pass later ask each node, "given the gradient arriving at your
            output, how much should flow to each of your inputs?"
        </p>
        <InsightBox>
            <p class="text-sm">A useful mental image: the forward pass lays down a <strong>trail</strong> as it goes, the graph from lesson 1.1, now filled with actual numbers and connections. Backprop simply follows that
            trail home in reverse. No trail, no backprop. This is why a framework can't just compute the answer and
            throw the steps away.</p>
        </InsightBox>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-14">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4">Key takeaways</h2>
        <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">1</span></div><p class="text-sm">The forward pass evaluates the graph from leaves to root, producing the output.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">2</span></div><p class="text-sm">While computing, each operation records its inputs and its kind, the trail backprop will follow.</p></div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3"><div class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-mt-accentLight flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5"><span class="text-mt-accent font-bold text-xs">3</span></div><p class="text-sm">Forward computes the answer; the recorded trail is what makes the backward pass possible.</p></div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <LessonNav
        prevHref="/graph/computation-as-a-graph" prevLabel="Prev: Computation as a Graph"
        nextHref="/graph/parameters-vs-activations" nextLabel="Next: Parameters vs Activations"
    />

</LessonLayout>
